    <a title="D.B. Woodling" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/41355949-d-b-woodling"><img alt="D.B. Woodling" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1456329046p2/41355949.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1559133210?book_show_action=true">Feb 24, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="D.B. Woodling" class="user" itemprop="url" name="D.B. Woodling" href="/user/show/41355949-d-b-woodling">D.B. Woodling</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>


          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">readers who appreciate classic literature</span></div>

        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1559133210" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5816063208132420891"><br/>In this short novel, published in 1935, the author accomplished what he has consistently achieved, awakening emotion through lifelike characters. Written during the depression, it is no wonder Steinbeck’s destitute but optimistic characters appealed to the masses. Their appreciation of basic needs — with the occasional bottle of wine and a lusty woman thrown in — struck a chord with so many experiencing similar hardships.<br/><br/>Though criticized for a demeaning portrayal of Mexican-Americans, Steinbeck</span>
  <span id="freeText5816063208132420891" style="display:none"><br />In this short novel, published in 1935, the author accomplished what he has consistently achieved, awakening emotion through lifelike characters. Written during the depression, it is no wonder Steinbeck’s destitute but optimistic characters appealed to the masses. Their appreciation of basic needs — with the occasional bottle of wine and a lusty woman thrown in — struck a chord with so many experiencing similar hardships.<br /><br />Though criticized for a demeaning portrayal of Mexican-Americans, Steinbeck's depiction of camaraderie and an Arthurian parallel defends such negative evaluation. Embodying the simple disposition of <i>Danny</i>, the main character, and his vagabond disciples, Steinbeck's narrative is both powerful and moving.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="5816063208132420891" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


